# Line-ending policy — ensures content identity across Windows laptop, Linux
# prod server, and cloud session environments.
#
# Without this file, Windows git's default `core.autocrlf=true` adds \r\n to
# working-tree files on checkout. Any tool that reads bytes directly (SCP, file
# manager copy, curl -F) will carry CRLF to servers, causing byte-level diffs
# against what git stores (LF). Session 35 hit this with the Apr 15 Klaim tape:
# the SCP'd prod copy had CRLF while the git-committed version had LF — byte-
# identical content but `git pull` refused to overwrite the untracked file.
#
# Rule: force LF for text formats analysts SCP or deploy; let git autodetect
# for source code (which is eol-agnostic).

# Loan tapes + analyst data — always LF (deploy.sh ships these via git pull,
# and SCP'd copies must match for the collision-detector in deploy.sh to
# auto-resolve cleanly).
*.csv      text eol=lf
*.json     text eol=lf
*.jsonl    text eol=lf
*.md       text eol=lf
*.yaml     text eol=lf
*.yml      text eol=lf

# Shell + deploy scripts — must be LF so they execute on Linux
*.sh       text eol=lf

# Binary formats — explicit so git doesn't try to convert
*.xlsx     binary
*.xlsm     binary
*.ods      binary
*.pdf      binary
*.docx     binary
*.pptx     binary
*.png      binary
*.jpg      binary
*.jpeg     binary
*.ico      binary
*.pkl      binary

# Python, JSX, CSS, HTML — let git autodetect (standard behaviour is fine)
*.py       text
*.jsx      text
*.js       text
*.tsx      text
*.ts       text
*.css      text
*.html     text
